Cell["\<\
HPL might produce better controllers and at much lower cost than other \
methods. HPL is cheap at scale: 100,000 judgments might cost $1000 from an \
online service like \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]Mechanical Turk.\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] Compare that to two hours\[CloseCurlyQuote] time, \
roughly, and barely enough to get started, for a consulting controls \
engineer. Furthermore, subjective human judgment is actually very refined. \
Almost anyone can tell the difference, at-a-glance, between an elegant \
gymnastic performance and a merely flawless one. How much does it cost to \
hand-write a robotic controller that produces elegant, not merely flawless, \
gymnastics? How about via standard reinforcement learning? How much does it \
cost to hand-craft a reward function that distinguishes elegant from \
flawless? If we could instead find such a controller for a few thousand \
dollars\[CloseCurlyQuote] worth of human judgments, is that not interesting?\
\>", "Text",
